{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585055"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:01:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:01:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14847"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14847"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.06,0.14,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7538"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58970"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7538"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14847"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44381"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"5651"},{"type":"tags","id":"9841"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18441"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18555"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58970"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following Rh blood group antigens is most likely to cause maternal alloimmunisation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["D","C","E","c","e"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Rh blood group system is complex and includes multiple antigens, with D being the most clinically significant. \u003Cstrong\u003ED\u003C/strong\u003E is highly immunogenic, with approximately 80% of D-negative individuals developing anti-D antibodies after exposure to D-positive red blood cells. This high immunogenicity is why anti-D prophylaxis is routinely given to D-negative pregnant women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC\u003C/strong\u003E antigen is much less immunogenic than D. While anti-C antibodies can cause haemolytic disease of the newborn, this occurs much less frequently than with anti-D antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EE\u003C/strong\u003E antigen, like C, has lower immunogenicity than D. Anti-E antibodies are occasionally seen but are less clinically significant than anti-D.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Ec\u003C/strong\u003E antigen, despite being common, rarely causes significant alloimmunisation. When anti-c antibodies do develop, they typically cause mild haemolytic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Ee\u003C/strong\u003E antigen is the least immunogenic of these Rh antigens. Anti-e antibodies are rarely encountered in clinical practice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the relative immunogenicity of Rh antigens is crucial for predicting risk in pregnancy. This knowledge underpins the rationale for routine antenatal anti-D prophylaxis, which has dramatically reduced the incidence of haemolytic disease of the newborn.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The D antigen is the most immunogenic of the Rh blood group system and is responsible for most cases of haemolytic disease of the newborn.","Anti-D antibodies develop in approximately 80% of D-negative individuals exposed to D-positive red cells.","Routine antenatal anti-D prophylaxis has dramatically reduced the incidence of Rh disease."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., Fausto, N., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (2014). Robbins and Cotran pathologic basis of disease, professional edition e-book. Elsevier health sciences","Dean L. Blood Groups and Red Cell Antigens [Internet]. Bethesda (MD): National Center for Biotechnology Information (US); 2005. Chapter 5, The ABO blood group. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK2267/","National Clinical Guideline Centre (UK). Blood Transfusion. London: National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE); 2015 Nov. (NICE Guideline, No. 24.) 16, Cryoprecipitate: thresholds and targets. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK338779/","Bastian IN, Rose WN. Educational Case: Alloimmunization of pregnancy. Acad Pathol. 2022 Aug 16;9(1):100040. doi: 10.1016/j.acpath.2022.100040. PMID: 36035765; PMCID: PMC9403359."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44381"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14847"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44381"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-03T23:23:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T19:17:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7538"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58970"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic